INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (3760,5,'2013-02-16 18:34:07','2013-02-16 18:34:07','<strong>When is the next cohort?</strong> Winter 2013\r\n\r\n<strong>How do we get in? </strong><a title=\"Apply\" href=\"http://localhost:8888/flashpoint/apply/\">Apply</a>. The deadline for applications is November 19.\r\n\r\n<strong>What kind of teams are you looking for?</strong> We need founders to be full-time committed to their startups and to have strong working relationships. The startup engineering work requires teams to have significant domain knowledge and to have relevant technical expertise ready to hand. We look for people who are demonstrably motivated to create scalable important businesses. All things equal, we\'d choose to work with exceptionally intelligent founders who are open in their thought processes, stable in temperament, conscientious in their ways, and relentlessly resourceful.\r\n\r\n<strong>What types of startups are you looking for?</strong> We like all startups, but especially technology startups. Atlanta is a great place for e-commerce, internet security, materials, consumer health, medical devices, computing, robotics, financial transactions, and logistics. With our connections to Georgia Tech and the Atlanta corporate community we look for  teams we think we may strongly advantage by providing access to resources in our networks.\r\n\r\n<strong>How did the first year go?</strong> Of the 30 teams in the first two cohorts, 28 continue to develop. In aggregate, the first cohort has received over $8 million in follow on funding. The second cohort, just finishing, has already received over $1 million in follow on funding from angels. Flashpoint teams are now backed by national first-tier firms and partners including Andreesen Horowitz (SF), Bessemer Ventures (SF), Sigma Partners (Boston), New World Ventures (Chicago), FFv (NYC), 500 Startups (Menlo Park), Starbucks Foundation, PwC, and southeastern angels through the ATA (Atlanta).\r\n\r\n<strong>Is Flashpoint an accelerator?</strong> It\'s more. Flashpoint has a startup engineering curriculum. We get startups moving incredibly fast and we teach founders the process. What we do dramatically reduces startup risks and costs.  Startups have a smaller chance of failing and at the same have a less expensive way to achieve success. Flashpoint is the opposite of an incubator.  The work is mostly out of the building.\r\n\r\n<strong>How is it similar to accelerators I know about?</strong>  Common attributes:  Many teams apply.  Flashpoint filters and accepts about a dozen into a cohort. Every team receives funding (about $25k for about 8%, don\'t get hung up on the numbers), enough to do the work without taking too much dilution. We connect teams with Flashpoint mentors <em>who have done startups before</em>. The Flashpoint community has dinner together at special  Tuesday night gatherings where teams present and mentors and Flashpoint alumni hang out with speakers who often fly in from the Bay Area, Boston or NYC. Teams work in great shared space in Tech Square. Each Flashpoint cohort runs four months and we run two cohorts a year. At the end of each cohort there are demo days for investors in Atlanta, NYC, and the Bay Area.\r\n\r\n<strong>I\'m a serial entrepreneur, is there anything here for me? </strong> Yes.  We can make a huge difference to you.  Here\'s one Flashpoint founder\'s perspective: \"I\'ve built enough successful companies and divisions of companies to know something. At Flashpoint I learned to think and understand things in a new way. It\'s changed how we\'re building our current company and how I\'ll build companies in the future.\" (<a href=\"http://about.me/kurtuhlir\">Kurt Uhlir</a>)\r\n\r\n<strong>We’ve already been working on our startup for a while. Is Flashpoint appropriate for us? </strong>Yes. Startup engineering practices and the Flashpoint program can help any startup.\r\n\r\n<strong>Do we have to legally form a company before the program starts? </strong>No. If you have a company, that is fine. If not, we will help you out.\r\n\r\n<strong>We’ve already taken funding. Can we still apply? </strong>Sure.\r\n\r\n<strong>Are there other sources of funding available? </strong>Yes. Many active angel investors and venture firms with early stage interests are looking to work with Flashpoint teams.\r\n\r\n<strong>What if we’re doing something expensive? </strong>Talk to us. The key is being able to get far enough along during the program to be of interest to later stage investors.\r\n\r\n<strong>Do we need to write a business plan? </strong>No. We do not read business plans. Nobody does anymore.  Not at this stage.\r\n\r\n<strong>Do we have to be in Atlanta for the program? </strong>Yes. See the application for more information.\r\n\r\n<strong>Our group has more than one idea. Can we submit more than one application? </strong>Pick the one you like best. Experience tells us to be somewhat less interested in your idea than in your team.\r\n\r\n<strong>I work at a large company. Can I apply?</strong> Flashpoint can solve your corporate innovation problem. Ask us how.\r\n\r\n<strong>Will you sign a Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)?</strong> No.  <strong>Then how do I know you won’t steal my idea? </strong>We do not sign NDAs. Our ability to operate depends on our integrity, so we guard it carefully.  More important, ideas are not very valuable in themselves. People and execution matters.  As far as we can tell, no one wants to get rich on your great idea, because they want to get rich on their dumb one. And, they see the situation in reverse.\r\n\r\n<strong>Is working in the Flashpoint space required?  </strong>Yes.  There is a great deal of value placed on sharing knowledge and experience with other teams.\r\n\r\n<strong>What’s the Flashpoint story? </strong>In the fall of 2010, Georgia Tech Executive Vice President for Research Dr. Stephen E. Cross created an innovation task force to support the institution’s strategic plan. This task force was led by Associate Vice President for Research Dr. Ravi Bellamkonda, and College of Computing Distinguished Professor Dr. Merrick Furst. Flashpoint was one of the task force’s recommendations to foster entrepreneurship and innovation. Now Flashpoint is beyond the experimental stage and we will scale it as a business.\r\n\r\n<strong>Is there really a Flashpoint Israel?</strong> Yes. We have an agreement with the Technion and with Microsoft\'s Accelerator in Israel. We will be teaching startup engineering to teams in their cohort, starting in December. We are expecting three teams to travel from Israel and join cohort 3 for February and March.\r\n\r\n<strong>I heard there is a Flashpoint Palo Alto?</strong> We have made arrangements to have space for two teams to be able to use shared workspace in Palo Alto.\r\n\r\n<strong>Who is running Flashpoint? </strong><strong>Merrick Furst</strong> is the founder and director of Flashpoint. As the first Distinguished Professor at the College of Computing, Merrick developed the highly regarded Threads curriculum. Merrick is also the co-founder of internet security firm <a href=\"http://www.damballa.com/\">Damballa</a>. Merrick was the founder and CEO of Essential Surfing Gear, a SF-based technology company acquired in 2001. Merrick was also president and director of the International Computer Science Institute at University of California at Berkeley.\r\n\r\n<strong>Are you hiring? </strong>Yes. Or, at least we will be soon. Get in touch. Tell us how you think you can help.\r\n\r\n<strong>Can I make a tax-deductible donation that would directly benefit the startup engineering work at Georgia Tech? </strong>Yes. Contact us.\r\n\r\n<strong>Does Flashpoint have a corporate sponsorship program?</strong>Yes. Check out the logos on the front page. Contact us.','FAQ','','inherit','closed','open','','3477-revision-3','','','2013-02-16 18:34:07','2013-02-16 18:34:07','',3477,'http://flashpoint.ei2.org/3477-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0);
